You said:
Is this cidr part of network?
ChatGPT said:
Yes â€” CIDR represents the network portion of an IP address. âœ…
Letâ€™s be precise so thereâ€™s no confusion.

Short Answer (Interview-ready)
CIDR defines how much of an IP address belongs to the network and how much belongs to hosts.

Detailed Explanation
An IPv4 address has 32 bits:

[ network bits | host bits ]
The CIDR suffix (/n) tells how many bits are network bits.

Example 1
10.0.0.0/16
/16 â†’ first 16 bits = network

remaining 16 bits = host

Binary view:

10.0 | 00000000 | 00000000 | 00000000
^^^^   ^^^^^^^^   host bits
network bits
So:

Network = 10.0

Hosts = 0.0 â†’ 255.255

Example 2
192.168.1.0/24
/24 â†’ first 24 bits = network

remaining 8 bits = host

Meaning:

Network: 192.168.1

Hosts: 0 â†’ 255

Important Clarification âš ï¸
âŒ CIDR is not an IP address by itself
âœ… CIDR is a rule that splits the IP into network + host parts

Think of it as:

IP address + CIDR = complete network definition

