CIDR (Classless Inter-Domain Routing) is a way to define a range of IP addresses using a network prefix instead of old fixed classes (A, B, C).

It is written as:

IP-address / prefix-length
Example:

10.0.0.0/16
1ï¸âƒ£ Why CIDR exists
Before CIDR, IPs were divided into rigid classes:

Class A â†’ /8

Class B â†’ /16

Class C â†’ /24

ğŸš¨ This caused huge IP wastage.

CIDR solves this by allowing flexible network sizes.

